00:24.882 --> 00:27.085
So the global optimality of this.

00:28.330 --> 00:31.094
And they go about convincing you of that.

00:31.174 --> 00:39.005
So the first thing that they convince you of is that if you fix the generator, the optimal discriminator is this.

00:39.105 --> 00:41.409
And we've already seen this in this drawing right here.

00:41.829 --> 00:54.507
So the optimal discriminator is simply the ratio of the data, of the likelihood of data versus the likelihood of the generated data.

00:54.487 --> 00:59.978
Okay, so you train, you always train this discriminator in the inner loop.

01:01.902 --> 01:05.669
And that's simply the consequence of this, of a point-wise.

01:06.110 --> 01:10.679
This is true point-wise, therefore it's true over the entire data distribution.

01:12.383 --> 01:14.166
In the next thing,

01:14.568 --> 01:27.260
they convinced you that the global minimum of the virtual training criterion, and this is the value function, this min max game, is achieved if and only if this holds.

01:27.820 --> 01:33.345
At that point, the training criterion achieves the value of negative log four.

01:33.886 --> 01:41.453
And again, this was already here, the fact that this has a global minimum,

01:41.433 --> 01:46.702
and it is achieved when the generator matches the data distribution, which is pretty cool.

01:47.202 --> 01:49.807
So in the proof, it's pretty simple, actually.

01:49.907 --> 01:58.561
They first say, look, if this is the case, we just simply plug that in, the discriminator will be confused.

01:58.581 --> 02:07.896
So if the generator exactly captures the data, the discriminator will have no clue what's going on, because it can't, because they're equal.

02:07.876 --> 02:12.185
So it must basically output the probability of one half everywhere.

02:12.746 --> 02:16.253
And then your objective becomes a constant negative log four.

02:17.375 --> 02:29.479
Now, if you then plug that into the other equation, you'll see that the training criterion ends up being negative log four plus twice the Jensen Shannon divergence between the data and the

02:29.459 --> 02:31.662
Um, generated distribution.

02:31.982 --> 02:40.534
And since this term here is always positive, that means that this thing here can never be less than negative log four.

02:41.195 --> 02:44.119
And therefore the negative log four is the optimum.

02:45.020 --> 02:45.320
Okay.

02:46.201 --> 02:49.886
That's, uh, it's that the proof is, is pretty cool.

02:50.087 --> 02:54.893
I have to say to show that this has the optimum at that place.

02:56.645 --> 03:10.263
And the last thing they convince you of is that this algorithm actually converges and the converges is simply predicated on the fact that if you look at each of these problems individually, they are convex.

03:10.484 --> 03:18.354
So, um, like here is convex in X for every alpha.

03:18.374 --> 03:21.178
So each of these are sort of convex problems.

03:21.779 --> 03:22.500
And then.

03:24.455 --> 03:28.019
it will naturally converge to their minimum.

03:29.761 --> 03:39.313
However, in practice adversarial nets represent a limited family of distributions via the function, and we optimize the parameters rather than the distribution itself.

03:39.813 --> 03:44.859
Using a multi-layer perceptron to define g introduces multiple critical points in parameter space.

03:45.300 --> 03:53.770
However, the excellent performance of the multi-layer perceptrons in practice suggests that they are a reasonable model to use despite their lack of theoretical guarantees.

03:53.750 --> 04:01.763
So they say if we could optimize this probability distribution directly, it is a convex problem and we'll always converge.

04:01.903 --> 04:07.832
But in practice, of course, we only optimize the parameters of an MLP or a CNN.

04:08.253 --> 04:14.543
And that doesn't always converge, but we have reasonable hopes that it will converge.

04:14.523 --> 04:23.302
Okay, so again, it's very much focused on convincing me that this is doing something sensible, which I hope now you are convinced.

04:23.322 --> 04:26.348
So there is a global optimum point.

04:26.468 --> 04:32.481
